## 🖥 Backend — `accounts` App Structure

```
backend/
├── config/
│   ├── settings.py
│   └── urls.py                  ← includes accounts.urls
│
└── accounts/
    ├── models.py                ← CustomUser model
    ├── serializers.py           ← RegisterSerializer, LoginSerializer, etc.
    ├── views.py                 ← all auth ViewSets/APIViews
    ├── urls.py                  ← all /api/auth/ routes
    └── utils.py                 ← generate_reset_code(), store/validate code
```

### CustomUser Model (`accounts/models.py`)
Extends `AbstractBaseUser` or just `AbstractUser`:
```
- email (unique, used as USERNAME_FIELD)
- first_name
- last_name
- is_active
- is_staff
- date_joined
```
We use **email** as the login field, not username.

### API Endpoints

| Method | URL | Description |
|--------|-----|-------------|
| POST | `/api/auth/register/` | Create account, return tokens |
| POST | `/api/auth/login/` | Login with email+password, return tokens |
| POST | `/api/auth/token/refresh/` | Get new access token via refresh token |
| POST | `/api/auth/forgot-password/` | Accept email, print code to terminal |
| POST | `/api/auth/verify-reset-code/` | Validate the code |
| POST | `/api/auth/reset-password/` | Set new password |
| GET  | `/api/auth/me/` | Return current user info (protected) |

### Reset Code Storage
Simple approach — store in Django's cache (in-memory, no Redis needed):
```python
from django.core.cache import cache
# cache.set(f"reset_{email}", code, timeout=600)  # 10 min expiry
# cache.get(f"reset_{email}")
```
Code is a random 6-digit number, printed to terminal with `print()`.

